<@4>
  On
    \{<^e><:h>ts</:h></^e> vs <^e><:h>ch</:h></^e>\},
    \{<^e><:h>ts'</:h></^e> vs <^e><:h>ch'</:h></^e>\} and
    \{<^e><:h>s</:h></^e> vs <^e><:h>sh</:h></^e>\}
  | ts-vs-ch
</@4>

<p>
  Modern Cantonese has merged the initials in the pairs
    \{將~<^e><:h>ts</:h>oeng</^e> vs 張~<^e><:h>ch</:h>oeng</^e>\},
    \{槍~<^e><:h>ts'</:h>oeng</^e> vs 昌~<^e><:h>ch'</:h>oeng</^e>\} and
    \{相~<^e><:h>s</:h>oeng</^e> vs 傷~<^e><:h>sh</:h>oeng</^e>\}.
  As noted by
  <@>
    Samuel Wells Williams
    | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Wells_Williams
    | Wikipedia: Samuel Wells Williams
  </@>
  in
  <@>
    《英華分韻撮要》
    | https://archive.org/details/tonicdictionaryo00will/page/n25/mode/1up
    | A tonic dictionary of the Chinese language in the Canton dialect
  </@>
  (1856, or 咸豐丙辰年):
</p>
<blockquote>
  The initials {ch} and {ts} are constantly confounded,
  and some persons are absolutely unable to detect the difference,
  more frequently calling the words under {ts} as {ch}, than contrawise.
</blockquote>

<p>
  The pre-merger distinctions are remnant only in most romanisations
  of district names in Hong Kong, e.g.
</p>
<ul>
  
  <li>
    \{<:v><^e>ts</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>ch</^e></:v>\}:
    將軍澳 (<:h>Ts</:h>eung Kwan O) and 荔枝角 (Lai <:h>Ch</:h>i Kok),
  </li>
  
  <li>
    \{<:v><^e>ts'</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>ch'</^e></:v>\}:
    荃灣 (<:h>Ts</:h>uen Wan) and 東涌 (Tung <:h>Ch</:h>ung), and
  </li>
  
  <li>
    \{<:v><^e>s</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>sh</^e></:v>\}:
    西灣河 (<:h>S</:h>ai Wan Ho) and 筲箕灣 (<:h>Sh</:h>au Kei Wan).
  </li>
  
</ul>
<p>
  Not all district romanisations follow the pre-merger consonants correctly though,
  e.g.~灣仔 should really be Wan <:h>Ts</:h>ai (not Wan <:h>Ch</:h>ai),
  and 彩虹 should be <:h>Ts</:h>oi Hung (not <:h>Ch</:h>oi Hung).
</p>

<p>
  Now despite the merging of those pairs of initials,
  I perceive a tendency for people to favour different consonants
  of the merger depending on the vowel which follows:
</p>


<!c><table>
  
  <tr>
    <th>Following vowel</th>
    <td>[aː]</td>
    <td>[ɐ]</td>
    <td>[ɛː]</td>
    <td>[e]</td>
    <td>[iː]</td>
    <td>[ɔː]</td>
    <td>[o]</td>
    <td>[uː]</td>
    <td>[œ]</td>
    <td>[ɵ]</td>
    <td>[yː]</td>
  </tr>
  
  <tr>
    <th rowspan="3">Favoured post-merger initial</th>
    <td class="centred-text" colspan="5"><:v><^e>ts</^e></:v></td>
    <td class="centred-text" colspan="6"><:v><^e>ch</^e></:v></td>
  </tr>
  
  <tr>
    <td class="centred-text" colspan="5"><:v><^e>ts'</^e></:v></td>
    <td class="centred-text" colspan="6"><:v><^e>ch'</^e></:v></td>
  </tr>
  
  <tr>
    <td class="centred-text" colspan="10"><:v><^e>s</^e></:v></td>
    <td class="centred-text"><:v><^e>sh</^e></:v></td>
  </tr>
  
</table></!c>

<p>
  The \{<:v><^e>s</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>sh</^e></:v>\} tendency
  is the strongest. I have never heard anyone pronounce 書,
    <^e><:h>sh</:h>u"</^e>~/~[ɕyː],
    as <^e><:h>s</:h>u"</^e>~/~[syː],
  and yet the vast majority of people will pronounce 石,
    <^e><:h>sh</:h>ek</^e>~/~[ɕɛːk̚],
    as <^e><:h>s</:h>ek</^e>~/~[sɛːk̚].
  The \{<:v><^e>ts</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>ch</^e></:v>\}
  and \{<:v><^e>ts'</^e></:v>~vs~<:v><^e>ch'</^e></:v>\} tendencies
  are not as strong, but still prevalent.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>I have decided to keep the pre-merger distinctions
  in my romanisation system for historical purposes,
  using the consonant given in
  <@>
    《分韻撮要》
    | https://ytenx.org/pyonh/
    | 韻典網：《分韻撮要》
  </@>
  unless noted otherwise.</strong>
</p>
<p>
  <strong>However, unless you want to sound really weird,
  I suggest pronouncing words using the
  appropriate favoured post-merger initial listed in the table above,
  rather than the pre-merger initial.</strong>
</p>


<@2> Finals (韻) | finals </@2>


<=>
  <@i> (<^e>aa</^e>) | #aa | aː </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>a</^e>) | #a | ɐ </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>e</^e>) | #e | ɛː and e </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>ee i</^e>) | #ee-i | iː and e </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>or o</^e>) | #or-o | ɔː and o </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>oo u</^e>) | #oo-u | uː and o </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>oe</^e>) | #oe | œ </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>_</^e>) | #_ | ɵ </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>u"</^e>) | #ue | yː </@i>
  <@i> (<^e>m ng</^e>) | #m-ng | m̩ and ŋ̍ </@i>
</=>

<p>
  If typesetting of the characters <:v><^e>oe</^e></:v>~(<`>U+0153</`>)
  and <:v><^e>u"</^e></:v>~(<`>U+00FC</`>) is inconvenient,
  you may use the ASCII-only substitutes <:v>oe</:v> and <:v>ue</:v>
  respectively.
</p>

